{
  "title": "Observation-Independent Reality",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8a806584090e767f",
      "text": "The thought that there would be an observation-independent reality is one that only a soulless babbling automaton can comfortably endure."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bfb5e3124834d690",
      "text": "Because it seems to me that for this purpose a metaphysical realism has come into the world. A metaphysical realism is a cognitive performance which shows itself adapted to an early intimating machine or device intelligence. Among these I include the disciplined and reflective study of pumps, hydraulic apparatus, cranes, pulleys, gears, levers, catapults, and also telescopes microscopes and inventions of all kinds such as compasses, clocks, motors, and so on. A machine and device intelligence had spanned a whole paradigm of scientificity that was needed to wash the religious implications out of a metaphysics without abandoning a metaphysics nonetheless."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bc7adfc385d479a8",
      "text": "I would like to put it this way: to adopt a metaphysical realism was the first reflective achievement of a new, i.e. modern form of scholarship, which I call methodological scholarship and which, following the Renaissance, had taken over the heritage of a metaphysical tradition and adapted it to its needs. These needs referred to seductive strategies of impressing, with which it was supposed to be shown that the marvels of technology could be explained in a completely natural way, i.e. that they obeyed natural law processes as objective facts, for the knowledge of which the assumption of an observation-dependent access to reality was not needed. Because: the whole questionabilities and errors, which result from the assumption of observation-independent facts, always only refer back to the occupation with methods, with which always one tried to deceive the observer, because one suspected him of the unconditional corruptness. So, if it should turn out that the results of an experimental set-up could not possibly be correct, the instruction for the deception of the observer was: Investigate your method of investigation, respectively investigate the method of investigation of the others and show yourself skeptical concerning their results. Doubts, skepticism and questionableness thus did not lead to the rejection of a learned use of methods, but to the reproduction of their persuasiveness, which succeeded only as long as one always cut the observer out of the calculation."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2dbddaffa129978a",
      "text": "The successes of this methodological erudition thus result from a highly strained and patiently persevered methodological skepticism, which consequently was able to hold out an ideal of objectivity without ever arriving at objective results in the majority of all cases. It was enough that noticed knowledge deficits could be postponed sufficiently often into the future and could be actually eliminated later. For the formation of a hope for progress, even for its hardening to an ideology of progress, the exceptional case was completely sufficient."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3acd088c5451f180",
      "text": "Thus, modern scholarship had come into being by self-circulation of the same ignorantia. Briefly formulated: a metaphysical realism was only an, albeit very useful, avoidance strategy, with which the further methodological involvement was motivated, which admittedly led to a constant differentiation and optimization of these methods, the culmination of which were nuclear fission, quantum physics, space travel and genetics. In this respect it is true: a metaphysical realism is nonsense, but useful, better said: has been useful."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "140e93f83cad2f03",
      "text": "Useful about it was that the constant cutting out of an observer from every calculation helped to experience the problems of the observation itself first. Quantum physicists and systems theorists know what I mean by this. Observation is not merely a mental process of the human mind. The facts of observation are more complicated. The devices come into question as observers."
    },
