        "id": "3acd088c5451f180",
        "text": "Thus, modern scholarship had come into being by self-circulation of the same ignorantia. Briefly formulated: a metaphysical realism was only an, albeit very useful, avoidance strategy, with which the further methodological involvement was motivated, which admittedly led to a constant differentiation and optimization of these methods, the culmination of which were nuclear fission, quantum physics, space travel and genetics. In this respect it is true: a metaphysical realism is nonsense, but useful, better said: has been useful. Useful about it was that the constant cutting out of an observer from every calculation helped to experience the problems of the observation itself first. Quantum physicists and systems theorists know what I mean by this. Observation is not merely a mental process of the human mind. The facts of observation are more complicated. The devices come into question as observers."
